pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals that she is not fluent, does not comprehend spoken language well, but is able to repeat phrases accurately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of aphasia is most likely?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Global aphasia","Broca\u2019s aphasia","Wernicke\u2019s aphasia","Mixed transcortical aphasia","Anomic aphasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with characteristics of \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed transcortical aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is marked by non-fluency, poor comprehension, but preserved repetition. This type of aphasia is often due to damage in the watershed areas of the brain, which are regions between the major cerebral arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobal aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E involves non-fluency, poor comprehension, and poor repetition, which does not match this patient\u0027s ability to repeat phrases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroca\u2019s aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by non-fluency and good comprehension, with impaired repetition, which does not align with this patient\u0027s preserved repetition ability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u2019s aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E involves fluent speech with poor comprehension and impaired repetition, which is inconsistent with this patient\u0027s non-fluency and preserved repetition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnomic aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by fluent speech and good comprehension, with difficulty in naming objects, which does not match this patient\u0027s presentation of non-fluency and poor comprehension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mixed transcortical aphasia is characterised by non-fluency, poor comprehension, but preserved repetition.","Aphasia types are differentiated by fluency, comprehension, and repetition abilities.","Global aphasia involves non-fluency, poor comprehension, and poor repetition."],"references":["Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021 Feb;21(2):221-234. doi: 10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976. Epub 2020 Dec 10. PMID: 33231117; PMCID: PMC7880889","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Tan, Y., Zhang, LM., Liang, Xl. et al. A literature review and meta-analysis of the optimal factors study of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in post-infarction aphasia. Eur J Med Res 29, 18 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40001-023-01525-5","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51958"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51958"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T17:02:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T17:03:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66505"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u